Rifampin PBPK Model

Nino Koci

2024-12-20

Introduction


For this project, I focused on developing a pharmacokinetic model for Rifampin, a common antibiotic used to treat tuberculosis. Since Rifampin is usually taken orally and works in the lungs where the tuberculosis bacterium primarily resides, the pharmacokinetic model would have to account for the drug circulating in the blood and reaching various tissues in the body before reaching its site of action. Therefore, a physiologically based pharmacokinetic(PBPK) model would be the best approach to the issue of vasculature, as it considers the different drug distributions in other tissues of the body. I have chosen to implement the model from Lyons et al.(2013), a PBPK model of Rifampin in mice. In this project, I aim to recreate not only the the mode, but I also intend to explore additional metrics not addressed in the original article. Inaddition, I will change the models dosing to an intravenous(IV) dose method to better understand the differences between oral and IVdoses.



Methods

Core Model Implementation


As pereviouly stated, I intend to fully implement the methodology outlined in Lyons et al., with a few changes to better suit the model implementation. I will not perform a Monte Carlo simulation of the parameter values, as the methodology is not well-defined. Instead, I will estimate the median change in Rifampin concentrations over time using the median parameter values from Table 1 and Table 2 of the article. This change will allow me to develop all figures in the article except Figure 11(Figure 7.A in the article) and the percentile-based values in Figures 3-6.


ODEdesign


To implement the model from Lyons et al., I used a MATLAB app, SimBiology, designed for PK/PD modeling. In the first phase of the model, I used graphical design to draw and implement the model diagram, adding additional elements that allow SimBiology to recognize the drug in each compartment and record reactions between compartments; these functions are automatically incorporated into the SimBiology code and returned as ODEs. The ODEs will therefore be implemented via a diagram based on Figure 1 and the ODEs in the appendix of Lyons et al. We can see in the diagram that each node, box, and line is specifically designed and programmed to represent the kinetics occurring within each compartment.

Parameter Estimation


Most of the parameters will come directly from the paper without changes.

Tissue volume and blood flow must be calculated using their fractional values and body weight in kilogram(kg). All the calculations are in the Excel sheet attached to the final submission. Blood/plasma partition is not explicitly stated in the article; however, based on the follow-up paper by Lyons et al.(2015), its value is 0.9.

Compartments will remain the same in this model. Although initially in kg, the volume will be set to liters(L) since we assume the tissues \(\frac{1kg}{L}\) density.

The dose will be represented in mg, the multiple of the drug dose, and the body weight in kilograms. To help generate Figures 2-7B from the article, the drug will have these dose variants: - 10\(\frac{mg}{kg}\) for plasma, liver, kidney, and lung - 15\(\frac{mg}{kg}\) for plasma only - 20\(\frac{mg}{kg}\) for plasma only - 40\(\frac{mg}{kg}\) for a single bolus dose for plasma only - 10\(\frac{mg}{kg}\) for three doses every 24 hours for plasma only

For all doses, the start time will be 0 hours.


Drug Administration and pharmacokinetics.


Species are compartment elements, and the Rifampin concentration will be the only element we will observe in a 120-hour timeframe. All initial concentrations of Rifampin in each compartment will be set to zero. Figures 3-7 show that the drug plasma concentration can be derived from the venous drug concentration using the blood-to-plasma partition coefficient. However, we will also examine drug concentrations in the lung, liver, and kidney compartments to reproduce Figure 4 from Lyons et al. Given that our dose is in mg and our volume is in L, the model will use \(\frac{mg}{mL}\) as the concentration unit. Lyons et al. report concentrations in tissues as \(\frac{g}{g}\) and in plasma as \(\frac{g}{mL}\). However, given the \(\frac{1kg}{L}\) assumption, all these concentration units should be in a 1:1 ratio with each other.

Variations in the 50% muscle/blood partition factor(PM) will be included and tested separately at a 10\(\frac{mg}{kg}\) single oral bolus dose to help recreate Figure 7.B.

For recreating Figure 2 and Table 3, we will use the non-compartmental analysis (NCA) and Observables features in the SimBiology model analyzer to calculate plasma AUC, \(t_{max}\), \(C_{max}\), and \(t_{half}\).


Performing Pertubations


The first perturbation will investigate the sensitive parameters in this model. We already did the PM through Figure 7B*. Therefore, we will use the variants function to achieve the same 50% change in the clearance rate (CL) and the absorption rate (ka). However, Bioavailability (Fa) is the percentage of the dose taken in, and, as such, it can never be less than 1. Therefore, Fa will be varied at 0.5 and 0.25.

The second perturbation in this model will be looking at how this drug can be changed from oral to IV. As such, we will keep the same 10\(\frac{mg}{kg}\) dose, both single and multiple, to see how the injectable dose has changed the dose-response in the plasma, liver, kidney, and lung. We will also investigate the AUC, \(C_{max}\), \(t_{max}\), and \(t_{half}\) in plasma for the single dose. The other single doses will not be recorded since 10\(\frac{mg}{kg}\) is sufficient to see the change.

Based on the siulation results we can make a few observations:

  • The plasma \(C_{max}\), \(t_{max}\), AUC and \(t_{half}\) results for the 10-$\frac{mg}{kg}$ single oral bolus dose are within the observed ranges of the values reported in the article, as seen in Table 1.

  • The plasma AUC curve in Figure 2.B from Lyons et al. saturates at a similar value and time (around 50 hours) to that of the recreated by the model in Figure 2.A.

    • In addition, we see that the remaining plasma results for the SimBiology simulated 10\(\frac{mg}{kg}\) single oral dose in Figures 3.A and Figure 4.A match relatively well with those of the median plasma concentration value from Lyons et al.(Figure 3.B and Figure 4.B respectively).

  • We can say the same thing for the multiple dosing in Figure 5.A for plasma which matches its counterpart in Lyons et al.(Figure 5.B).

  • Liver results for the SimBiology model simulated 10\(\frac{mg}{kg}\) single oral bolus dose in Figure 3.A and Figure 4.A also matches relatively well with those of the median liver concentration value from Lyons et al.(Figure 3.B and Figure 4.B respectively). And just like in plasma, its multiple dosing in Figure 5.A matches its counterpart in Lyons et al.(Figure 5.B).

  • We may also conclude that the 10\(\frac{mg}{kg}\) single oral bolus dose response for lungs and kidneys in the recreated Figure 4.A also matches the median dose result from Lyons et al. (Figure 4.B).

  • The recreated Figure 3.A and Figure 6.A also confirm that the 15\(\frac{mg}{kg}\), 20\(\frac{mg}{kg}\), and 40\(\frac{mg}{kg}\) single doses match the median response in Lyons et al.(Figure 3.B and Figure 6.B respectively).

  • Finally, the results seen in Figure 7.A closely match its counterpart from Lyons et al.(Figure 7.B).

Overall, the SimBiology model results indicate that it was successfully implemented with the median parameter values and yielded results similar to those of the non-compartmental analysis. Indicating that the recreation was relatively successful. However in hthe future we must attempt to recreate the Monte Carlo simulation in MATLAB.



Perturbations

Exploring the sensitivity seen in Lyons et al.

Varying the three additional parameters(ka, CL, Fa), we can make a few observations:

  • By varying the ka, we see in Figure 8 that a higher ka correlates with the reaction reaching the maximum concentration faster. This aligns with the logic that a higher absorption rate means the drug is absorbed into the plasma much more quickly.
  • FIGURE 8 - 10\(\frac{mg}{mL}\) baseline plasma Rifampin concentration over time with a 50% increase and decrease in absorption rate(ka)
  • By varying the clearance rate (CL), we observe in Figure 9 that the drug retained in the system increases as the CL decreases. This follows the logic that the lower the drug is eliminated from the system through the excretory system, the more of the drug remains in the system.
  • FIGURE 9 - 10\(\frac{mg}{mL}\) baseline plasma Rifampin concentration with a 50% increase and decrease in clearance rate(CL).
  • In both cases, we see a lower Fa rate correlated to a lower maximum concentration of the drug in plasma. This follows the logic that we will get a smaller response by decreasing the amount of drug that enters the system.
  • FIGURE 10 - 10\(\frac{mg}{mL}\) baseline mouse plasma Rifampin concentration with a 50% increase and decrease in Bioavailability(Fa).
  • FIGURE 11 -Pearson correlation coefficients between sensitive parameters and 10\(\frac{mg}{kg}\) single oral dose of Rifampin plasma concentration as a function of time.

However, if we compare all four sensitivity parameters we pertubed via SimBiology with the Pearson correlation results seen in Figure 11, where we notice that the maximum drug concentration in plasma will directly correlate with Fa and ka and inversely with CL and PM. PM and, secondly, Fa appear to have a greater impact on the 10\(\frac{mg}{kg}\) dose, as seen in Figure 7 and Figure 10. These results directly correlate with the sensitivity analysis in Figure 11 by Lyons et al.



Intra Venous(IV) Rifampin injection

  • FIGURE 12 - 10\(\frac{mg}{mL}\) IV bolus dose Rifampin concentrations in mouse plasma, lung, liver, and kidney.


  • FIGURE 13 - 10\(\frac{mg}{mL}\) repeated IV bolus dose Rifampin concentrations in mouse plasma and liver.


In the second perturbation set, Figure 12 and Figure 13 show that the drug immediately enters the blood and spreads much more rapidly throughout the system, peaking almost instantly. We see in Table 1 that the \(C_{max}\) and \(t_{max}\) of the drug in plasma change as the drugs absorption in the body is no longer solely dependent on the gut, which absorbs the drug and sends it to the liver before it spreads in the veins. This latter part may be why the liver drug concentration is tamer than the other compartments. We get a much faster, stronger response by removing intermediary steps. However, we also note in Table 1 and Figure 11 that \(t_{half}\) and AUC remain within the range of the regular bolus response, indicating that, regardless of the injection route, the drug will retain its half-life, and the amount of drug in the bloodstream remains constant over time.
